It wasn’t until the 1980s when the majority of Asian women began leaving their traditional roles as housewives in order to find their individualism, to identify with their personal identities, to experience college, and to achieve the self-worth they had never acknowledged as women. Symbolically, it is as if they forgot their families and blamed these women for the follies and the choices they, as women, believed was the only way. Through women leaving the mainstream and engaging in other aspects, the gender roles of both men and women in Korea have shifted. The overwhelming opinion of the majority is that as a society we are plotted into a default setting—women will stay at home and bare children, and men will work all day, come home, and beat the wife and children. However, women are fighting to leave these gender roles behind, thus proving a fast-growing change.

Today we turn on the news and see that more and more women are adopting highly respected positions in Korean institutions. They are succeeding as businesswomen, scientists, inventors, doctors, lawyers, and many other communicative and educational disciplines. Today we go about our normal lives and conduct our day-to-day business with these new “employing” women. When women strictly came from a humble background—that of being home-makers—they were able to get by as husbands meant to be the providers.
